nversational practices and dynamics shaped Kennedy's perception of the options available to him, thereby influencing his decisions and ultimately the outcome of the crisis. David Gibson looks not just at the positions taken by Kennedy and his advisers but how those positions were articulated, challenged, revised, and sometimes ignored. He argues that Kennedy's decisions arose from the intersection of distant events unfolding in Cuba, Moscow, and the high seas with the immediate conversational minutia of turn-taking, storytelling, argument, and justification. In particular, Gibson shows how Kennedy's group told and retold particular stories again and again, sometimes settling upon a course of action only after the most frightening consequences were omitted or actively suppressed. Talk at the Brink presents an image of Kennedy's response to the Cuban missile crisis that is sharply at odds with previous scholarship, and has important implications for our understanding of decision making, deliberation, social interaction, and historical contingency.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aConversation analysisvCase studies. 0aCuban Missile Crisis, 1962. 0aDecision makingzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aPublic administrationzUnited StatesxDecision makingvCase studies. 0aSocial interactionzUnited StatesvCase studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aBay of Pigs.  aCuba.  aCuban missile crisis.  aExComm.  aExecutive Committee of the National Security Council.  aJohn F. Kennedy.  aKhrushchev.  aSoviet missiles.  aWhite House meetings.  ablockade.  achoice.  acollaborative narration.  acrisis talks.  adecision making.  adecision-making process.  adeliberation.  afuture.  alinguistic expression.  anarrative relevance.  anuclear missiles.  asecret